<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFibonacci_sequence&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"India">India</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFibonacci_sequence&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: India"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#History" ti=
tle=3D"Golden ratio">Golden ratio =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fibonacci_Sanskrit_prosody.svg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/0/06/Fibonacci_Sanskrit_prosody.svg/250px-Fibonacci_Sanskrit_prosody=
.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"512"></a><figcaption>T=
hirteen (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub>7</sub></span>) ways of arran=
ging long and short syllables in a cadence of length six. Eight (<span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub>6</sub></span>) end with a short syllable and fi=
ve (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub>5</sub></span>) end with a long sy=
llable.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The Fibonacci sequence appears in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Indian_mathematics" title=3D"Indian mathematics">Indian mathematics</a>,=
 in connection with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit_proso=
dy" title=3D"Sanskrit prosody">Sanskrit prosody</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-His=
toriaMathematica_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-HistoriaMathematica-4"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-knuth-v1_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-knuth-v1-11"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003197_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio200319=
7-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> In the Sanskrit poetic tradition, there was interest in e=
numerating all patterns of long (L) syllables of 2 units duration, juxtapos=
ed with short (S) syllables of 1 unit duration. Counting the different patt=
erns of successive L and S with a given total duration results in the Fibon=
acci numbers: the number of patterns of duration <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> units is <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>F</i><sub><i>m</i>+1</sub></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Donald_Knuth_2006_5=
0_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonac=
ci_sequence#cite_note-Donald_Knuth_2006_50-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Knowledge of the Fibonacci sequence was expressed as early as <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pingala" title=3D"Pingala">Pingala</a> (=
<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr>&nbsp;450&nbsp;BC=E2=80=93200&nbsp;BC). Sing=
h cites Pingala's cryptic formula <i>misrau cha</i> ("the two are mixed") a=
nd scholars who interpret it in context as saying that the number of patter=
ns for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> b=
eats (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub><i>m</i>+1</sub></span>) is obta=
ined by adding one [S] to the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub><i>m</i>=
</sub></span> cases and one [L] to the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub=
><i>m</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span> cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_no=
te-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bharata_Muni" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bharata Muni">Bharata Muni</a> also expresses=
 knowledge of the sequence in the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Natya_Shastra" title=3D"Natya Shastra">Natya Shastra</a></i> (<abbr titl=
e=3D"circa">c.</abbr>&nbsp;100&nbsp;BC=E2=80=93<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</ab=
br>&nbsp;350&nbsp;AD).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GlobalScience_3-1" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note=
-GlobalScience-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-HistoriaMathematica_4-2" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequen=
ce#cite_note-HistoriaMathematica-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
However, the clearest exposition of the sequence arises in the work of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virahanka" title=3D"Virahanka">Virahan=
ka</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr>&nbsp;700&nbsp;AD), whose own work i=
s lost, but is available in a quotation by Gopala (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.=
</abbr>&nbsp;1135):<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003197_12-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite=
_note-FOOTNOTELivio2003197-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote><p>Variations of two earlier meters [is the variation]&nbsp;...=
  For example, for [a meter of length] four, variations of meters of two [a=
nd] three being mixed, five happens. [works out examples 8, 13, 21]&nbsp;..=
. In this way, the process should be followed in all <i>m=C4=81tr=C4=81-v=
=E1=B9=9Bttas</i> [prosodic combinations].<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite=
_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hemachandra" title=3D"Hemachand=
ra">Hemachandra</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr>&nbsp;1150) is credited=
 with knowledge of the sequence as well,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GlobalScience_3=
-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_=
sequence#cite_note-GlobalScience-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> writing that "the sum of the=
 last and the one before the last is the number&nbsp;... of the next m=C4=
=81tr=C4=81-v=E1=B9=9Btta."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003197=E2=80=
=93198_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ibonacci_sequence#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2003197%E2%80%93198-16"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Europe">Europe</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFibonacci_sequence&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Europe"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Liber_abbaci_magliab_f124r.jpg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/0/04/Liber_abbaci_magliab_f124r.jpg/330px-Liber_abbaci_magliab_f124r=
.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"310" height=3D"474" class=3D"mw-file-elem=
ent" data-file-width=3D"744" data-file-height=3D"1137"></a><figcaption>A pa=
ge of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci" title=3D"Fibonacc=
i">Fibonacci</a>'s <span title=3D"Latin-language text"><i lang=3D"la"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liber_Abaci" title=3D"Liber Abaci">Libe=
r Abaci</a></i></span> from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Na=
tional_Central_Library_(Florence)" title=3D"National Central Library (Flore=
nce)">Biblioteca Nazionale di Firenze</a> showing (in box on right) 13 entr=
ies of the Fibonacci sequence:<br> the indices from present to XII (months)=
 as Latin ordinals and Roman numerals and the numbers (of rabbit pairs) as =
Hindu-Arabic numerals starting with 1, 2, 3, 5 and ending with 377.</figcap=
tion></figure>
<p>The Fibonacci sequence first appears in the book <span title=3D"Latin-la=
nguage text"><i lang=3D"la"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liber_=
Abaci" title=3D"Liber Abaci">Liber Abaci</a></i></span> (<i>The Book of Cal=
culation</i>, 1202) by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci" =
title=3D"Fibonacci">Fibonacci</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESigler2002404=
=E2=80=93405_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-FOOTNOTESigler2002404%E2%80%93405-18"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> where it is =
used to calculate the growth of rabbit populations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequ=
ence#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Fibonacci considers the growth of an idealiz=
ed (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology" title=3D"Biology">bio=
logically</a> unrealistic) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabbit"=
 title=3D"Rabbit">rabbit</a> population, assuming that: a newly born breedi=
ng pair of rabbits are put in a field; each breeding pair mates at the age =
of one month, and at the end of their second month they always produce anot=
her pair of rabbits; and rabbits never die, but continue breeding forever. =
Fibonacci posed the rabbit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathema=
tical_problem" title=3D"Mathematical problem">math problem</a>: how many pa=
irs will there be in one year?
</p>
<ul><li>At the end of the first month, they mate, but there is still only 1=
 pair.</li>
<li>At the end of the second month they produce a new pair, so there are 2 =
pairs in the field.</li>
<li>At the end of the third month, the original pair produce a second pair,=
 but the second pair only mate to gestate for a month, so there are 3 pairs=
 in all.</li>
<li>At the end of the fourth month, the original pair has produced yet anot=
her new pair, and the pair born two months ago also produces their first pa=
ir, making 5 pairs.</li></ul>
<p>At the end of the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">n</span>-th month, the number of pairs of rabbits is equal to the numbe=
r of mature pairs (that is, the number of pairs in month <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>n</i> =E2=80=93 2</span>) plus the number of pairs alive last mont=
h (month <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=80=93 1</span>). The number i=
n the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>-th=
 month is the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</=
span>-th Fibonacci number.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-21"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>The name "Fibonacci sequence" was first used by the 19th-century num=
ber theorist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89douard_Lucas" t=
itle=3D"=C3=89douard Lucas">=C3=89douard Lucas</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequ=
ence#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fibonacci_Rabbits.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/a/af/Fibonacci_Rabbits.svg/500px-Fibonacci_Rabbits.svg.png" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"380" height=3D"295" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"397"></a><figcaption>Solution to=
 Fibonacci rabbit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_pro=
blem" title=3D"Mathematical problem">problem</a>: In a growing idealized po=
pulation, the number of rabbit pairs form the Fibonacci sequence. At <i>the=
 end of the n</i>th month, the number of pairs is equal to <i>F<sub>n.</sub=
></i></figcaption></figure>
