~\!\left({\frac {5}{n}}\right)},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3fdb68cb3f222cc5da8b63965b4197aae98b00ed" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.338ex; width:12.15ex; height:4.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n\=
mid F_{n\,-~\!\left({\frac {5}{n}}\right)},}"></span>
where the Legendre symbol has been replaced by the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Jacobi_symbol" title=3D"Jacobi symbol">Jacobi symbol</a>, =
then this is evidence that <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">n</span> is a prime, and if it fails to hold, then <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is definitely not a pr=
ime. If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> =
is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composite_number" title=3D"Comp=
osite number">composite</a> and satisfies the formula, then <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is a <i>Fibonacci pseud=
oprime</i>. When <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
m</span> is large&nbsp;=E2=80=93 say a 500-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Bit" title=3D"Bit">bit</a> number&nbsp;=E2=80=93 then we can calcu=
late <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub><i>m</i></sub> (mod <i>n</i>)</sp=
an> efficiently using the matrix form. Thus
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\begin{pmatrix}F_{m+1}&amp;F_{m}\\F_{m}&amp;F_{m-1}\en=
d{pmatrix}}\equiv {\begin{pmatrix}1&amp;1\\1&amp;0\end{pmatrix}}^{m}{\pmod =
{n}}.}">
