<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fibonacci_primes">Fibonacci=
 primes</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFibo=
nacci_sequence&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: F=
ibonacci primes"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_prime" tit=
le=3D"Fibonacci prime">Fibonacci prime</a></div>
<p>A <i>Fibonacci prime</i> is a Fibonacci number that is <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime</a>. The=
 first few are:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd>2, 3, 5, 13, 89, 233, 1597, 28657, 514229, ...</dd></dl>
<p>Fibonacci primes with thousands of digits have been found, but it is not=
 known whether there are infinitely many.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_=
note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub><i>kn</i></sub></span> is divis=
ible by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub><i>n</i></sub></span>, so, apa=
rt from <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub>4</sub> =3D 3</span>, any Fibo=
nacci prime must have a prime index. As there are <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Arbitrarily_large" title=3D"Arbitrarily large">arbitrarily =
long</a> runs of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composite_number"=
 title=3D"Composite number">composite numbers</a>, there are therefore also=
 arbitrarily long runs of composite Fibonacci numbers.
</p><p>No Fibonacci number greater than <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><su=
b>6</sub> =3D 8</span> is one greater or one less than a prime number.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The only nontrivial <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_=
number" title=3D"Square number">square</a> Fibonacci number is 144.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  Attila Peth=C5=91 proved i=
n 2001 that there is only a finite number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Perfect_power" title=3D"Perfect power">perfect power</a> Fibonac=
ci numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 2006, =
Y. Bugeaud, M. Mignotte, and S. Siksek proved that 8 and 144 are the only s=
uch non-trivial perfect powers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-52"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>1, 3, 21, and 55 are the only <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Triangular_number" title=3D"Triangular number">triangular</a> Fibonacci =
numbers, which was <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjecture" tit=
le=3D"Conjecture">conjectured</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Verner_Emil_Hoggatt_Jr." title=3D"Verner Emil Hoggatt Jr.">Vern Hoggatt<=
/a> and proved by Luo Ming.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-53"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p>No Fibonacci number can be a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Perfect_number" title=3D"Perfect number">perfect number</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Luca2000_54-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-Luca2000-54"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More generall=
y, no Fibonacci number other than 1 can be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Multiply_perfect_number" title=3D"Multiply perfect number">multipl=
y perfect</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BGLLHT2011_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-BGLLHT201=
1-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> and no ratio of two Fibonacci numbers can be perfect.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-LucaMH2010_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-LucaMH2010-56"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Prime_divisors">Prime divis=
ors</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFibonacc=
i_sequence&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Prime=
 divisors"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>With the exceptions of 1, 8 and 144 (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><su=
b>1</sub> =3D <i>F</i><sub>2</sub></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>=
<sub>6</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub>12</sub></span=
>) every Fibonacci number has a prime factor that is not a factor of any sm=
aller Fibonacci number (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carmichael=
%27s_theorem" title=3D"Carmichael's theorem">Carmichael's theorem</a>).<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As a result, 8 and 144 (=
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub>6</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>F</i><sub>12</sub></span>) are the only Fibonacci numbers that are =
the product of other Fibonacci numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_no=
te-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The divisibility of Fibonacci numbers by a prime <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> is related to the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendre_symbol" title=3D"Legendre symbol=
">Legendre symbol</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inli=
ne"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"di=
splay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D=
"{\displaystyle {\bigl (}{\tfrac {p}{5}}{\bigr )}}">
