<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Periodicity_modulo_n">Perio=
dicity modulo <i>n</i></h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.p=
hp?title=3DFibonacci_sequence&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"=
Edit section: Periodicity modulo n"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pisano_period" title=
=3D"Pisano period">Pisano period</a></div>
<p>If the members of the Fibonacci sequence are taken mod&nbsp;<span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, the resulting sequ=
ence is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_sequence" title=
=3D"Periodic sequence">periodic</a> with period at most&nbsp;<span class=3D=
"texhtml">6<i>n</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-65" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-65"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> The lengths of the periods for various <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> form the so-called <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pisano_period" title=3D"Pisano period">Pisano period=
s</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Determining a =
general formula for the Pisano periods is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Open_problem" title=3D"Open problem">open problem</a>, which inc=
ludes as a subproblem a special instance of the problem of finding the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicative_order" title=3D"Multipl=
icative order">multiplicative order</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modular integer=
</a> or of an element in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_=
field" title=3D"Finite field">finite field</a>. However, for any particular=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, the Pi=
sano period may be found as an instance of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Cycle_detection" title=3D"Cycle detection">cycle detection</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generalizations">Generaliza=
tions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFibona=
cci_sequence&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Gen=
eralizations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalizations_of_F=
ibonacci_numbers" title=3D"Generalizations of Fibonacci numbers">Generaliza=
tions of Fibonacci numbers</a></div>
<p>The Fibonacci sequence is one of the simplest and earliest known sequenc=
es defined by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recurrence_relatio=
n" title=3D"Recurrence relation">recurrence relation</a>, and specifically =
by a linear <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Difference_equation" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Difference equation">difference equation</a>.=
 All these sequences may be viewed as generalizations of the Fibonacci sequ=
ence. In particular, Binet's formula may be generalized to any sequence tha=
t is a solution of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_recurr=
ence_with_constant_coefficients" title=3D"Linear recurrence with constant c=
oefficients">homogeneous linear difference equation with constant coefficie=
nts</a>.
</p><p>Some specific examples that are close, in some sense, to the Fibonac=
ci sequence include:
</p>
<ul><li>Generalizing the index to negative integers to produce the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negafibonacci" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Negafibonacci">negafibonacci</a> numbers.</li>
<li>Generalizing the index to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real=
_number" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a> using a modification of Bin=
et's formula.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MathWorld_37-2" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-MathWorld-3=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup></li>
<li>Starting with other integers. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Lucas_number" title=3D"Lucas number">Lucas numbers</a> have <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>L</i><sub>1</sub> =3D 1</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i=
><sub>2</sub> =3D 3</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L<sub>n</sub></i=
> =3D <i>L</i><sub><i>n</i>=E2=88=921</sub> + <i>L</i><sub><i>n</i>=E2=88=
=922</sub></span>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primefree_seque=
nce" title=3D"Primefree sequence">Primefree sequences</a> use the Fibonacci=
 recursion with other starting points to generate sequences in which all nu=
mbers are composite.</li>
<li>Letting a number be a linear function (other than the sum) of the 2 pre=
ceding numbers. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pell_number" t=
itle=3D"Pell number">Pell numbers</a> have <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P<sub=
>n</sub></i> =3D 2<i>P</i><sub><i>n</i>=E2=88=921</sub> + <i>P</i><sub><i>n=
</i>=E2=88=922</sub></span>. If the coefficient of the preceding value is a=
ssigned a variable value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">x</span>, the result is the sequence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_polynomials" title=3D"Fibonacci polynomials">Fibona=
cci polynomials</a>.</li>
<li>Not adding the immediately preceding numbers. The <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padovan_sequence" title=3D"Padovan sequence">Padovan se=
quence</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perrin_number" titl=
e=3D"Perrin number">Perrin numbers</a> have <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i=
>(<i>n</i>) =3D <i>P</i>(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 2) + <i>P</i>(<i>n</i> =E2=88=
=92 3)</span>.</li>
<li>Generating the next number by adding 3 numbers (tribonacci numbers), 4 =
numbers (tetranacci numbers), or more. The resulting sequences are known as=
 <i>n-Step Fibonacci numbers</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-67"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFibonacci_se=
quence&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Applicati=
