0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_s=
equence#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The Fibonacci numbers are also an example of a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Complete_sequence" title=3D"Complete sequence">complete se=
quence</a>. This means that every positive integer can be written as a sum =
of Fibonacci numbers, where any one number is used once at most.</li>
<li>Moreover, every positive integer can be written in a unique way as the =
sum of <i>one or more</i> distinct Fibonacci numbers in such a way that the=
