<p>Fibonacci sequences appear in biological settings,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-79=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_se=
quence#cite_note-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> such as branching in trees, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phyllotaxis" title=3D"Phyllotaxis">arrangement o=
f leaves on a stem</a>, the fruitlets of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Pineapple" title=3D"Pineapple">pineapple</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_s=
equence#cite_note-80"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the flowering of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Artichoke" title=3D"Artichoke">artichoke</a>, the leaves o=
f the spiral aloe<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-81"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (Al=
oe polyphylla), the arrangement of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pine_cone" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pine cone">pine cone</a>,<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the family tree of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honeybee" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Honeybee">honeybees</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-83"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kepler" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kepler"=
>Kepler</a> pointed out the presence of the Fibonacci sequence in nature, u=
sing it to explain the (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rat=
io" title=3D"Golden ratio">golden ratio</a>-related) <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagon" title=3D"Pentagon">pentagonal</a> form of some=
 flowers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003110_85-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-FOOT=
NOTELivio2003110-85"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Field <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Leucanthemum_vulgare" title=3D"Leucanthemum vulgare">daisies</a> most =
often have petals in counts of Fibonacci numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNO=
TELivio2003112=E2=80=9313_86-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2003112%E2%80%9=
313-86"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> In 1830, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_=
Friedrich_Schimper" title=3D"Karl Friedrich Schimper">Karl Friedrich Schimp=
er</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Braun" title=
=3D"Alexander Braun">Alexander Braun</a> discovered that the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parastichy" title=3D"Parastichy">parastichies</a=
> (spiral <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phyllotaxis" title=3D"Ph=
yllotaxis">phyllotaxis</a>) of plants were frequently expressed as fraction=
s involving Fibonacci numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-87"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Przemys%C5%82aw_Prusinkiewi=
cz" title=3D"Przemys=C5=82aw Prusinkiewicz">Przemys=C5=82aw Prusinkiewicz</=
a> advanced the idea that real instances can in part be understood as the e=
xpression of certain algebraic constraints on <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Free_group" title=3D"Free group">free groups</a>, specifically =
as certain <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L-system" title=3D"L-sy=
stem">Lindenmayer grammars</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-88" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-88"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p>
