</p><p>where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</s=
pan> is the index number of the floret and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> is a constant scaling factor; the floret=
s thus lie on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_spiral" t=
itle=3D"Fermat's spiral">Fermat's spiral</a>. The divergence <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angle">angle</a>, approximately =
137.51=C2=B0, is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_angle"=
 title=3D"Golden angle">golden angle</a>, dividing the circle in the golden=
 ratio. Because this ratio is irrational, no floret has a neighbor at exact=
ly the same angle from the center, so the florets pack efficiently. Because=
 the rational approximations to the golden ratio are of the form <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>(=E2=80=89<i>j</i>):<i>F</i>(=E2=80=89<i>j</i> + 1)</=
span>, the nearest neighbors of floret number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> are those at <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>n</i> =C2=B1 <i>F</i>(=E2=80=89<i>j</i>)</span> for some index <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">j</span>, which depends on=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span>, the di=
stance from the center. Sunflowers and similar flowers most commonly have s=
pirals of florets in clockwise and counter-clockwise directions in the amou=
nt of adjacent Fibonacci numbers,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003112_9=
0-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci=
_sequence#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2003112-90"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> typically counted =
by the outermost range of radii.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-91" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-91">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>Fibonacci numbers also appear in the ancestral pedigrees of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bee" title=3D"Bee">bees</a> (which are <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haplodiploid" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Haplodiploid">haplodiploids</a>), according to the following rules=
:
</p>
<ul><li>If an egg is laid but not fertilized, it produces a male (or <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drone_(bee)" title=3D"Drone (bee)">drone=
 bee</a> in honeybees).</li>
<li>If, however, an egg is fertilized, it produces a female.</li></ul>
<p>Thus, a male bee always has one parent, and a female bee has two. If one=
 traces the pedigree of any male bee (1 bee), he has 1 parent (1 bee), 2 gr=
andparents, 3 great-grandparents, 5 great-great-grandparents, and so on. Th=
is sequence of numbers of parents is the Fibonacci sequence. The number of =
ancestors at each level, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub><i>n</i></sub=
></span>, is the number of female ancestors, which is <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>F</i><sub><i>n</i>=E2=88=921</sub></span>, plus the number of male an=
cestors, which is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub><i>n</i>=E2=88=922</=
sub></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-92" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-92"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-93" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>91=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is under the unrealist=
ic assumption that the ancestors at each level are otherwise unrelated.
</p>
