<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other">Other</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFibonacci_sequence&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D35" title=3D"Edit section: Other"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul><li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optics" title=3D"Optics=
">optics</a>, when a beam of light shines at an angle through two stacked t=
ransparent plates of different materials of different <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Refractive_index" title=3D"Refractive index">refractive=
 indexes</a>, it may reflect off three surfaces: the top, middle, and botto=
m surfaces of the two plates. The number of different beam paths that have =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> reflecti=
ons, for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> &gt; 1</span>, is the <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>-th Fibonacci number=
. (However, when <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =3D 1</span>, there are t=
hree reflection paths, not two, one for each of the three surfaces.)<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio200398=E2=80=9399_95-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-FOOTNOTELi=
vio200398%E2%80%9399-95"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_retracement" title=
=3D"Fibonacci retracement">Fibonacci retracement</a> levels are widely used=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technical_analysis" title=3D"T=
echnical analysis">technical analysis</a> for financial market trading.</li=
>
<li>Since the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conversion_of_units"=
 title=3D"Conversion of units">conversion</a> factor 1.609344 for miles to =
kilometers is close to the golden ratio, the decomposition of distance in m=
iles into a sum of Fibonacci numbers becomes nearly the kilometer sum when =
the Fibonacci numbers are replaced by their successors. This method amounts=
 to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix" title=3D"Radix">radix=
</a> 2 number <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Processor_register" =
title=3D"Processor register">register</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Golden_ratio_base" title=3D"Golden ratio base">golden ratio base=
</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</span=
> being shifted. To convert from kilometers to miles, shift the register do=
wn the Fibonacci sequence instead.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-96" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-96=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup></li>
<li>The measured values of voltages and currents in the infinite resistor c=
hain circuit (also called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resi=
stor_ladder" title=3D"Resistor ladder">resistor ladder</a> or infinite seri=
es-parallel circuit) follow the Fibonacci sequence. The intermediate result=
s of adding the alternating series and parallel resistances yields fraction=
s composed of consecutive Fibonacci numbers. The equivalent resistance of t=
he entire circuit equals the golden ratio.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-97" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite=
_note-97"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Brasch et al. 2012 show how a generalized Fibonacci sequence also can b=
e connected to the field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Econom=
ics" title=3D"Economics">economics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Brasch_et_al._20=
12_98-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibon=
acci_sequence#cite_note-Brasch_et_al._2012-98"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In particular, i=
t is shown how a generalized Fibonacci sequence enters the control function=
 of finite-horizon dynamic optimisation problems with one state and one con=
trol variable. The procedure is illustrated in an example often referred to=
 as the Brock=E2=80=93Mirman economic growth model.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mario_Merz" title=3D"Mario Mer=
z">Mario Merz</a> included the Fibonacci sequence in some of his artworks b=
eginning in 1970.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003176_99-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_n=
ote-FOOTNOTELivio2003176-99"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>97<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Schillinger" title=3D"J=
oseph Schillinger">Joseph Schillinger</a> (1895=E2=80=931943) developed <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schillinger_System" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Schillinger System">a system of composition</a> which uses Fi=
bonacci intervals in some of its melodies; he viewed these as the musical c=
ounterpart to the elaborate harmony evident within nature.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-FOOTNOTELivio2003193_100-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2003193-100"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> See also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#Mus=
ic" title=3D"Golden ratio">Golden ratio =C2=A7&nbsp;Music</a>.</li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_development" title=
=3D"Software development">software development</a>, Fibonacci numbers are o=
ften used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agile_management" tit=
le=3D"Agile management">agile</a> teams operating under the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scrum_(software_development)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Scrum (software development)">Scrum</a> framework to size their=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_backlog" title=3D"Product=
 backlog">product backlog</a> items.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-101" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#cite_note=
-101"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>99<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup></li></ul>
